    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.27"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">221 Neihardt Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">27</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        411 West 115 Street
                        New York City 
                        August 27, 1929
                    </dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear John Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have just received a letter from Longmans, stating that a review copy of Houston Peterson's <hi rend="underline">The Book of Sonnet Sequences</hi> had been sent to the Post Dispatch, in your name: this at my suggestion. I shall be deeply grateful if you would personally review this book, for it is the most general recognition I have ever yet received and your word and name will mean much in my future, and, I think, by so doing, your will be helping far greater Powers than we are conscious of. We<add>,</add> perhaps<add>,</add> are under-officers in some great campaign, and I <hi rend="underline">know</hi> that you hold an outpost. Peterson, also, wuold<sic>would</sic> be greatly gratified if you would write on the book for the Dispatch.</p>
                
                <p>You should have had a number of letters from me on your own poems, which were my companions during my five weeks in Maine. I travelled with you on all your ways, and the high crest was reached in Hugh Glass. You will know how much I loved the poem when I told you I spent one evening reading it alou<del>s</del><add>d</add> to a dear friend.</p>
                
                <p>I hope I amy<sic>may</sic> soon have a line from you.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Thomas S. Jones, Jr.</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <note type="recipient">Thomas <hi rend="caps">S.</hi> Jones, Jr. the poet; one of the <unclear>first</unclear> we have produced. Do you know him?</note>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
